1
00:00:11,120 --> 00:00:13,440
The fundamental root of it all building block

2
00:00:13,440 --> 00:00:16,105
for linear algebra is the vector. So it's

3
00:00:16,105 --> 00:00:17,465
worth making sure that we're all on the

4
00:00:17,465 --> 00:00:20,025
same page about what exactly a vector is.

5
00:00:20,345 --> 00:00:22,905
You see, broadly speaking, there are three distinct

6
00:00:22,905 --> 00:00:25,385
but related ideas about vectors, which I'll call

7
00:00:25,385 --> 00:00:27,945
the physics student perspective, the computer science student

8
00:00:27,945 --> 00:00:30,025
perspective, and the mathematician's perspective.

9
00:00:30,640 --> 00:00:32,960
The physics student perspective is that vectors are

10
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:34,640
arrows pointing in space.

11
00:00:34,880 --> 00:00:37,360
What defines a given vector is its length

12
00:00:37,360 --> 00:00:39,600
and the direction it's pointing. But as long

13
00:00:39,600 --> 00:00:41,120
as those two facts are the same, you

14
00:00:41,120 --> 00:00:42,560
can move it all around and it's still

15
00:00:42,560 --> 00:00:43,120
the same vector.

16
00:00:43,825 --> 00:00:45,505
Vectors that live in the flat plane are

17
00:00:45,505 --> 00:00:47,825
two dimensional, and those sitting in broader space

18
00:00:47,825 --> 00:00:50,385
that you and I live in are three-dimensional.

19
00:00:51,585 --> 00:00:54,225
The computer science perspective is that vectors are

20
00:00:54,225 --> 00:00:55,505
ordered lists of numbers.

21
00:00:56,060 --> 00:00:57,740
For example, let's say you were doing some

22
00:00:57,740 --> 00:01:00,620
analytics about house prices and the only features

23
00:01:00,620 --> 00:01:03,020
you cared about were square footage and price.

24
00:01:03,180 --> 00:01:04,940
You might model each house with a pair

25
00:01:04,940 --> 00:01:07,500
of numbers, the first indicating square footage and

26
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:08,940
the second indicating price.

27
00:01:09,180 --> 00:01:10,620
Notice the order matters here.

28
00:01:12,595 --> 00:01:14,755
In the lingo, you'd be modeling houses as

29
00:01:14,755 --> 00:01:17,715
two dimensional vectors where in this context vector

30
00:01:17,715 --> 00:01:19,635
is pretty much just a fancy word for

31
00:01:19,635 --> 00:01:22,035
list and what makes it two dimensional is

32
00:01:22,035 --> 00:01:23,395
the fact that the length of that list

33
00:01:23,395 --> 00:01:23,955
is two.

34
00:01:25,580 --> 00:01:27,900
The mathematician, on the other hand, seeks to

35
00:01:27,900 --> 00:01:30,780
generalize both these views, basically saying that a

36
00:01:30,780 --> 00:01:32,860
vector can be anything where there's a sensible

37
00:01:32,860 --> 00:01:35,420
notion of adding two vectors and multiplying a

38
00:01:35,420 --> 00:01:37,500
vector by a number, operations that I'll talk

39
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:38,700
about later on in this video.

40
00:01:39,345 --> 00:01:41,825
The details of this view are rather abstract,

41
00:01:41,825 --> 00:01:43,665
and I actually think it's healthy to ignore

42
00:01:43,665 --> 00:01:45,585
it until the last video of this series

43
00:01:45,585 --> 00:01:48,225
favoring a more concrete setting in the interim.

44
00:01:48,305 --> 00:01:49,665
But the reason I bring it up here

45
00:01:49,665 --> 00:01:51,505
is that it hints at the fact that

46
00:01:51,505 --> 00:01:54,065
the ideas of vector addition and multiplication by

47
00:01:54,065 --> 00:01:56,760
numbers will play an important role throughout linear

48
00:01:56,760 --> 00:01:57,480
algebra.

49
00:01:57,800 --> 00:01:59,960
But before I talk about those operations, let's

50
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:01,960
just settle in on a specific thought to

51
00:02:01,960 --> 00:02:03,560
have in mind when I say the word

52
00:02:03,560 --> 00:02:04,280
vector.

53
00:02:04,520 --> 00:02:06,440
Given the geometric focus that I'm shooting for

54
00:02:06,440 --> 00:02:08,760
here, whenever I introduce a new topic involving

55
00:02:08,760 --> 00:02:11,065
vectors, I want you to first think about

56
00:02:11,065 --> 00:02:12,905
an arrow and specifically

57
00:02:12,905 --> 00:02:15,785
think about that arrow inside a coordinate system

58
00:02:15,785 --> 00:02:17,945
like the x y plane with its tail

59
00:02:17,945 --> 00:02:19,065
sitting at the origin.

60
00:02:19,545 --> 00:02:20,825
This is a little bit different from the

61
00:02:20,825 --> 00:02:23,625
physics student perspective where vectors can freely sit

62
00:02:23,625 --> 00:02:26,440
anywhere they want in space. In linear algebra,

63
00:02:26,440 --> 00:02:28,600
it's almost always the case that your vector

64
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:30,440
will be rooted at the origin.

65
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:33,320
Then, once you understand a new concept in

66
00:02:33,320 --> 00:02:35,240
the context of arrows in space,

67
00:02:35,480 --> 00:02:37,080
we'll translate it over to the list of

68
00:02:37,080 --> 00:02:38,760
numbers point of view, which we can do

69
00:02:38,760 --> 00:02:40,440
by considering the coordinates of the vector.

70
00:02:41,135 --> 00:02:42,735
Now, while I'm sure that many of you

71
00:02:42,735 --> 00:02:45,135
are already familiar with this coordinate system, it's

72
00:02:45,135 --> 00:02:47,375
worth walking through explicitly since this is where

73
00:02:47,375 --> 00:02:49,535
all of the important back and forth happens

74
00:02:49,535 --> 00:02:51,855
between the two perspectives of linear algebra.

75
00:02:52,495 --> 00:02:54,495
Focusing our attention on two dimensions for the

76
00:02:54,495 --> 00:02:56,640
moment, you have a horizontal line called the

77
00:02:56,640 --> 00:02:58,960
x axis and a vertical line called the

78
00:02:58,960 --> 00:02:59,760
y axis.

79
00:03:00,080 --> 00:03:01,760
The place where they intersect is called the

80
00:03:01,760 --> 00:03:03,440
origin, which you should think of as the

81
00:03:03,440 --> 00:03:04,960
center of space and the root of all

82
00:03:04,960 --> 00:03:05,680
vectors.

83
00:03:06,160 --> 00:03:08,480
After choosing an arbitrary length to represent one,

84
00:03:08,480 --> 00:03:10,155
you make tick marks on each axis to

85
00:03:10,155 --> 00:03:11,435
represent this distance.

86
00:03:12,075 --> 00:03:13,515
When I want to convey the idea of

87
00:03:13,515 --> 00:03:15,355
two d space as a whole, which you'll

88
00:03:15,355 --> 00:03:16,795
see comes up a lot in these videos,

89
00:03:16,795 --> 00:03:18,635
I'll extend these tick marks to make grid

90
00:03:18,635 --> 00:03:20,555
lines. But right now, they'll actually get a

91
00:03:20,555 --> 00:03:21,435
little bit in the way.

92
00:03:21,835 --> 00:03:23,920
The coordinates of a vector is a pair

93
00:03:23,920 --> 00:03:26,720
of numbers that basically gives instructions for how

94
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:28,240
to get from the tail of that vector

95
00:03:28,240 --> 00:03:30,240
at the origin to its tip.

96
00:03:30,640 --> 00:03:32,320
The first number tells you how far to

97
00:03:32,320 --> 00:03:34,880
walk along the x axis, positive numbers indicating

98
00:03:34,880 --> 00:03:38,225
rightward motion, negative numbers indicating leftward motion, and

99
00:03:38,225 --> 00:03:40,225
the second number tells you how far to

100
00:03:40,225 --> 00:03:43,025
walk parallel to the y axis after that.

101
00:03:43,105 --> 00:03:45,825
Positive numbers indicating upward motion and negative numbers

102
00:03:45,825 --> 00:03:47,505
indicating downward motion.

103
00:03:47,985 --> 00:03:50,465
To distinguish vectors from points, the convention is

104
00:03:50,465 --> 00:03:52,305
to write this pair of numbers vertically with

105
00:03:52,305 --> 00:03:53,745
square brackets around them.

106
00:03:56,120 --> 00:03:58,280
Every pair of numbers gives you one and

107
00:03:58,280 --> 00:03:59,640
only one vector,

108
00:03:59,800 --> 00:04:02,040
and every vector is associated with one and

109
00:04:02,040 --> 00:04:03,720
only one pair of numbers.

110
00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:05,720
What about in three dimensions?

111
00:04:05,800 --> 00:04:08,120
Well, you add a third axis called the

112
00:04:08,120 --> 00:04:10,655
z axis, which is perpendicular to both the

113
00:04:10,655 --> 00:04:12,175
x and y axis

114
00:04:12,255 --> 00:04:14,575
and in this case each vector is associated

115
00:04:14,575 --> 00:04:16,895
with an ordered triplet of numbers. The first

116
00:04:16,895 --> 00:04:18,575
tells you how far to move along the

117
00:04:18,575 --> 00:04:20,815
x axis, the second tells you how far

118
00:04:20,815 --> 00:04:23,300
to move parallel to the y axis, and

119
00:04:23,300 --> 00:04:24,660
the third one tells you how far to

120
00:04:24,660 --> 00:04:27,700
then move parallel to this new z axis.

121
00:04:28,100 --> 00:04:30,580
Every triplet of numbers gives you one unique

122
00:04:30,580 --> 00:04:31,620
vector in space,

123
00:04:31,860 --> 00:04:34,100
and every vector in space gives you exactly

124
00:04:34,100 --> 00:04:35,220
one triplet of numbers.

125
00:04:36,465 --> 00:04:39,265
Alright, so back to vector addition and multiplication

126
00:04:39,265 --> 00:04:41,905
by numbers. After all, every topic in linear

127
00:04:41,905 --> 00:04:43,985
algebra is going to center around these two

128
00:04:43,985 --> 00:04:44,705
operations.

129
00:04:45,025 --> 00:04:47,345
Luckily, each one's pretty straightforward to define.

130
00:04:48,060 --> 00:04:50,060
Let's say we have two vectors, one pointing

131
00:04:50,060 --> 00:04:51,660
up and a little to the right and

132
00:04:51,660 --> 00:04:53,100
the other one pointing right and down a

133
00:04:53,100 --> 00:04:56,060
bit. To add these two vectors, move the

134
00:04:56,060 --> 00:04:58,300
second one so that its tail sits at

135
00:04:58,300 --> 00:04:59,580
the tip of the first one.

136
00:05:00,060 --> 00:05:02,575
Then, if you draw a new vector from

137
00:05:02,575 --> 00:05:04,335
the tail of the first one to where

138
00:05:04,335 --> 00:05:06,335
the tip of the second one now sits,

139
00:05:06,575 --> 00:05:08,735
that new vector is their sum.

140
00:05:11,615 --> 00:05:13,990
This definition of addition, by the way, is

141
00:05:13,990 --> 00:05:16,150
pretty much the only time in linear algebra

142
00:05:16,150 --> 00:05:18,150
where we let vectors stray away from the

143
00:05:18,150 --> 00:05:18,870
origin.

144
00:05:19,270 --> 00:05:21,030
Now, why is this a reasonable thing to

145
00:05:21,030 --> 00:05:23,030
do? Why this definition of addition and not

146
00:05:23,030 --> 00:05:23,990
some other one?

147
00:05:25,110 --> 00:05:26,550
Well, the way I like to think about

148
00:05:26,550 --> 00:05:28,710
it is that each vector represents a certain

149
00:05:28,710 --> 00:05:31,275
movement, a step with a certain distance and

150
00:05:31,275 --> 00:05:32,395
direction in space.

151
00:05:33,835 --> 00:05:35,355
If you take a step along the first

152
00:05:35,355 --> 00:05:35,995
vector,

153
00:05:36,235 --> 00:05:37,675
then take a step in the direction and

154
00:05:37,675 --> 00:05:40,395
distance described by the second vector, the overall

155
00:05:40,395 --> 00:05:41,915
effect is just the same as if you

156
00:05:41,915 --> 00:05:43,755
moved along the sum of those two vectors

157
00:05:43,755 --> 00:05:44,315
to start with.

158
00:05:44,980 --> 00:05:46,660
You could think about this as an extension

159
00:05:46,660 --> 00:05:48,500
of how we think about adding numbers on

160
00:05:48,500 --> 00:05:49,460
a number line.

161
00:05:49,780 --> 00:05:51,140
One way that we teach kids to think

162
00:05:51,140 --> 00:05:53,540
about this, say with two plus five, is

163
00:05:53,540 --> 00:05:55,140
to think of moving two steps to the

164
00:05:55,140 --> 00:05:57,380
right followed by another five steps to the

165
00:05:57,380 --> 00:05:59,675
right. The overall effect is the same as

166
00:05:59,675 --> 00:06:01,195
if you just took seven steps to the

167
00:06:01,195 --> 00:06:01,675
right.

168
00:06:02,155 --> 00:06:04,475
In fact, let's see how vector addition looks

169
00:06:04,475 --> 00:06:05,435
numerically.

170
00:06:05,755 --> 00:06:08,475
The first vector here has coordinates one, two,

171
00:06:09,435 --> 00:06:11,835
and the second one has coordinates three, negative

172
00:06:11,835 --> 00:06:12,075
one.

173
00:06:14,170 --> 00:06:15,930
When you take the vector sum using this

174
00:06:15,930 --> 00:06:17,770
tip to tail method, you can think of

175
00:06:17,770 --> 00:06:19,850
a four step path from the origin to

176
00:06:19,850 --> 00:06:21,930
the tip of the second vector. Walk one

177
00:06:21,930 --> 00:06:23,930
to the right, then two up, then three

178
00:06:23,930 --> 00:06:25,210
to the right, then one down.

179
00:06:26,205 --> 00:06:28,525
Reorganizing these steps so that you first do

180
00:06:28,525 --> 00:06:30,445
all of the rightward motion, then do all

181
00:06:30,445 --> 00:06:32,285
the vertical motion, you can read it as

182
00:06:32,285 --> 00:06:34,605
saying, first move one plus three to the

183
00:06:34,605 --> 00:06:37,805
right, then move two minus one up.

184
00:06:39,860 --> 00:06:42,180
So the new vector has coordinates one plus

185
00:06:42,180 --> 00:06:44,900
three and two plus negative one.

186
00:06:45,220 --> 00:06:47,620
In general, vector addition in this list of

187
00:06:47,620 --> 00:06:48,740
numbers conception

188
00:06:48,740 --> 00:06:51,060
looks like matching up their terms and adding

189
00:06:51,060 --> 00:06:51,780
each one together.

190
00:06:54,435 --> 00:06:57,555
The other fundamental vector operation is multiplication by

191
00:06:57,555 --> 00:06:59,795
a number. Now, is best understood just by

192
00:06:59,795 --> 00:07:01,235
looking at a few examples.

193
00:07:01,475 --> 00:07:03,395
If you take the number two and multiply

194
00:07:03,395 --> 00:07:04,435
it by a given vector,

195
00:07:04,850 --> 00:07:07,090
it means you stretch out that vector so

196
00:07:07,090 --> 00:07:08,770
that it's two times as long as when

197
00:07:08,770 --> 00:07:09,490
you started.

198
00:07:09,970 --> 00:07:12,050
If you multiply that vector by say one

199
00:07:12,050 --> 00:07:14,530
third, it means you squish it down so

200
00:07:14,530 --> 00:07:16,370
that it's one third the original length.

201
00:07:17,025 --> 00:07:19,345
When you multiply it by a negative number,

202
00:07:19,345 --> 00:07:21,025
like negative 1.8,

203
00:07:21,025 --> 00:07:23,665
then the vector first gets flipped around, then

204
00:07:23,665 --> 00:07:26,065
stretched out by that factor of 1.8.

205
00:07:26,865 --> 00:07:29,345
This process of stretching or squishing or sometimes

206
00:07:29,345 --> 00:07:31,665
reversing the direction of a vector is called

207
00:07:31,665 --> 00:07:32,465
scaling.

208
00:07:32,970 --> 00:07:34,970
And whenever you catch a number like two

209
00:07:34,970 --> 00:07:37,690
or one third or negative 1.8 acting like

210
00:07:37,690 --> 00:07:39,450
this, scaling some vector,

211
00:07:39,610 --> 00:07:40,970
you call it a scalar.

212
00:07:41,450 --> 00:07:43,850
In fact, throughout linear algebra, one of the

213
00:07:43,850 --> 00:07:46,250
main things that numbers do is scale vectors.

214
00:07:46,615 --> 00:07:48,455
So it's common to use the word scalar

215
00:07:48,455 --> 00:07:50,935
pretty much interchangeably with the word number.

216
00:07:51,495 --> 00:07:53,815
Numerically, stretching out a vector by a factor

217
00:07:53,815 --> 00:07:57,015
of say two corresponds with multiplying each of

218
00:07:57,015 --> 00:07:59,095
its components by that factor two.

219
00:07:59,670 --> 00:08:01,510
So in the conception of vectors as lists

220
00:08:01,510 --> 00:08:02,310
of numbers,

221
00:08:02,470 --> 00:08:04,870
multiplying a given vector by a scalar means

222
00:08:04,870 --> 00:08:07,430
multiplying each one of those components by that

223
00:08:07,430 --> 00:08:08,310
scalar.

224
00:08:09,830 --> 00:08:11,510
You'll see in the following videos what I

225
00:08:11,510 --> 00:08:13,510
mean when I say that linear algebra topics

226
00:08:13,510 --> 00:08:16,815
tend to revolve around these two fundamental operations,

227
00:08:16,895 --> 00:08:19,055
vector addition and scalar multiplication.

228
00:08:19,455 --> 00:08:20,815
And I'll talk more in the last video

229
00:08:20,815 --> 00:08:23,535
about how and why the mathematician thinks only

230
00:08:23,535 --> 00:08:26,815
about these operations independent and abstracted away from

231
00:08:26,815 --> 00:08:28,575
however you choose to represent vectors.

232
00:08:29,180 --> 00:08:31,260
In truth, it doesn't matter whether you think

233
00:08:31,260 --> 00:08:33,900
about vectors as fundamentally being arrows in space,

234
00:08:33,900 --> 00:08:35,740
like I'm suggesting you do, that happen to

235
00:08:35,740 --> 00:08:37,500
have a nice numerical representation,

236
00:08:37,660 --> 00:08:39,820
or fundamentally as lists of numbers that happen

237
00:08:39,820 --> 00:08:41,420
to have a nice geometric interpretation.

238
00:08:41,905 --> 00:08:44,305
The usefulness of linear algebra has less to

239
00:08:44,305 --> 00:08:45,985
do with either one of these views than

240
00:08:45,985 --> 00:08:48,145
it does with the ability to translate back

241
00:08:48,145 --> 00:08:50,545
and forth between them. It gives the data

242
00:08:50,545 --> 00:08:53,025
analyst a nice way to conceptualize many lists

243
00:08:53,025 --> 00:08:55,490
of numbers in a visual way which can

244
00:08:55,490 --> 00:08:57,810
seriously clarify patterns in data and give a

245
00:08:57,810 --> 00:09:00,450
global view of what certain operations do. And

246
00:09:00,450 --> 00:09:02,130
on the flip side, it gives people like

247
00:09:02,130 --> 00:09:05,410
physicists and computer graphics programmers a language to

248
00:09:05,410 --> 00:09:08,805
describe space and the manipulation of space using

249
00:09:08,805 --> 00:09:10,325
numbers that can be crunched and run through

250
00:09:10,325 --> 00:09:11,125
a computer.

251
00:09:11,605 --> 00:09:14,325
When I do mathy animations, for example, I

252
00:09:14,325 --> 00:09:16,325
start by thinking about what's actually going on

253
00:09:16,325 --> 00:09:18,245
in space and then get the computer to

254
00:09:18,245 --> 00:09:19,765
represent things numerically,

255
00:09:19,925 --> 00:09:21,925
thereby figuring out where to place the pixels

256
00:09:21,925 --> 00:09:24,230
on the screen. And doing that usually relies

257
00:09:24,230 --> 00:09:26,390
on a lot of linear algebra understanding.

258
00:09:27,350 --> 00:09:29,110
So there are your vector basics, and in

259
00:09:29,110 --> 00:09:30,870
the next video, I'll start getting into some

260
00:09:30,870 --> 00:09:33,750
pretty neat concepts surrounding vectors like span, bases,

261
00:09:33,750 --> 00:09:35,590
and linear dependence. See you then.
